17 would violate a rule adopted by the board.
18 (4) Deposit or cause or allow the deposit of any contaminants or
19 solid waste upon the land, except through the use of sanitary
20 landfills, incineration, composting, garbage grinding, or another
21 method acceptable to the board.
22 (5) Dump or cause or allow the open dumping of garbage or of
23 any other solid waste in violation of rules adopted by the board.
24 (6) Dispose of solid waste in, upon, or within the limits of or
25 adjacent to a public highway, state park, state nature preserve, or
26 recreation area or in or immediately adjacent to a lake or stream,
27 except:
28 (A) in proper containers provided for sanitary storage of the
29 solid waste; or
30 (B) as a part of a sanitary landfill operation or other land
31 disposal method approved by the department.
32 (7) Construct, install, operate, conduct, or modify, without prior
33 approval of the department, any equipment or facility of any type
34 that may:
35 (A) cause or contribute to pollution; or
36 (B) be designed to prevent pollution.
37 However, the commissioner or the board may approve
38 experimental uses of any equipment, facility, or pollution control
39 device that is considered necessary for the further development of
40 the state of the art of pollution control.
41 (8) Conduct any salvage operation or open dump by open burning
42 or burn, cause, or allow the burning of any solid waste in a
SB 277—LS 6849/DI 150

150
1 manner that violates either:
2 (A) the air pollution control laws; or
3 (B) the rules adopted by the board.
4 (9) Commence construction of a proposed hazardous waste
5 facility without having first:
6 (A) filed an application for; and
7 (B) received;
8 a permit from the department.
9 (10) Commence or engage in the operation of a hazardous waste
10 facility without having first obtained a permit from the
11 department.
12 (11) Deliver any hazardous waste to a hazardous waste facility
13 that:
14 (A) is not approved; or
15 (B) does not hold a permit from the department.
16 (12) Cause or allow the transportation of a hazardous waste
17 without a manifest if a manifest is required by law.
18 (13) Violate any:
19 (A) condition;
20 (B) limitation; or
21 (C) stipulation;
22 placed upon a certificate of environmental compatibility by the
23 hazardous waste facility site approval authority or any other
24 provision of IC 13-22-10.
25 (14) Apply or allow the application of used oil to any ground
26 surface, except for purposes of treatment in accordance with a
27 permit issued by the department under any of the following:
28 (A) IC 13-15. except IC 13-15-9.
29 (B) IC 13-17-11.
30 (C) IC 13-18-18.
31 (D) IC 13-20-1.
32 (15) Commence construction of a solid waste incinerator without
33 first obtaining a permit from the department under IC 13-20-8.
34 (16) Commence operation of a solid waste incinerator without
35 first obtaining the approval of the department under IC 13-20-8.
36 SECTION 315. IC 13-30-10-1.5, AS AMENDED BY P.L.181-2018,
37 SECTION 14, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
38 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 1.5. (a) Except as provided in subsection (b), a
39 person regulated under IC 13-22 who knowingly:
40 (1) transports hazardous waste to an unpermitted facility;
41 (2) treats, stores, or disposes of hazardous waste without a permit
42 issued by the department under IC 13-22; or
SB 277—LS 6849/DI 150

151
1 (3) transports, treats, stores, disposes, recycles, or causes to be
2 transported used oil regulated under rules adopted by the board
3 without a manifest or in violation of the standards established by
4 the department for the management of used oil;
5 commits a Class B misdemeanor.
6 (b) Notwithstanding the maximum fine provisions of IC 35-50-3-3,
7 criminal fines for a person convicted of an offense described in
8 subsection (a) shall be assessable in a maximum amount of not less
9 than ten thousand dollars ($10,000) per day per violation.
10 (c) Except as provided in subsection (d), a person regulated under
11 IC 13-17 who knowingly violates:
12 (1) any applicable requirements of IC 13-17-4, IC 13-17-5,
13 IC 13-17-6, IC 13-17-7, IC 13-17-8, IC 13-17-9, IC 13-17-10, or
14 IC 13-17-13 or of rules of the board implementing the chapters
15 referred to in this subdivision;
16 (2) any condition of a permit issued by the department under
17 IC 13-17; or
18 (3) any fee or filing requirement in IC 13-17, including the
19 requirement to file an application for a permit under IC 13-17;
20 commits a Class C misdemeanor.
21 (d) Notwithstanding the maximum fine provisions of IC 35-50-3-4,
22 criminal fines for a person convicted of an offense described in
23 subsection (c) shall be assessable in a maximum amount of not less
24 than ten thousand dollars ($10,000) per day per violation.
25 (e) Except as provided in subsection (f), a person who willfully or
26 negligently violates:
27 (1) any applicable standards or limitations of IC 13-18-3-2.4,
28 IC 13-18-4-5, IC 13-18-12, IC 13-18-14, IC 13-18-15, or
29 IC 13-18-16 or of rules of the board implementing the chapters
30 referred to in this subdivision;
31 (2) any condition of a National Pollutant Discharge Elimination
32 System permit issued by the department under IC 13-18-19 or
33 rules adopted by the board under IC 13-18-19;
34 (3) any National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System Permit
35 filing requirement under IC 13-18-19; or
36 (4) any condition of a permit issued by the department in
37 accordance with the requirements of 33 U.S.C. 1344;
38 commits a Class A misdemeanor.
39 (f) Notwithstanding the maximum fine provisions of IC 35-50-3-2,
40 criminal fines for a person convicted of an offense described in
41 subsection (e) shall be assessable in a maximum amount of not less
42 than ten thousand dollars ($10,000) per day per violation.
SB 277—LS 6849/DI 150

152
1 (g) A person who willfully or recklessly violates any applicable
2 standards or limitations of IC 13-18-8 commits a Class B misdemeanor.
3 (h) A person who willfully or recklessly violates any applicable
4 standards or limitations of IC 13-18-9, IC 13-18-10, or IC 13-18-10.5
5 commits a Class C misdemeanor.
6 (i) A person who:
7 (1) knowingly commits any act described in subsection (a), (c), or
8 (e); and
9 (2) knows that commission of the act places another person in
10 imminent danger of death or serious bodily injury;
11 commits a Level 4 felony. However, the offense is a Level 3 felony if
12 it results in serious bodily injury to any person, and a Level 2 felony if
13 it results in the death of any person.
14 (j) It shall be a defense to an offense described in subsection (i) that
15 the person charged:
16 (1) did not know; or
17 (2) could not reasonably have been expected to know;
18 that the violation would place another person in imminent danger or
19 threat of serious bodily injury. For the purposes of subsection (i), a
20 person is responsible only for the person's own actual awareness or
21 actual belief, and knowledge by another person may not be attributed
22 to the person.
23 (k) The penalties under this section apply regardless of whether a
24 person uses electronic submissions or paper documents to accomplish
25 the actions described in this section.
